{
"entities": [
{
"type": "rule",
"canonical_name": "Aluminum",
"aliases": ["The everyday metal"],
"claims": [
{
"text": "Aluminum is described as a light silvery metal widely used in consumer products such as soda cans, foil, cookware, and aircraft parts.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
},
{
"text": "Aluminum is identified as the third most abundant element in the Earths crust, making it readily available and inexpensive to produce.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
},
{
"text": "Aluminum is not a required nutrient and may accumulate in the body through repeated exposure.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
},
{
"text": "Excessive aluminum exposure is discussed as a possible contributor to neurological concerns including conditions such as Alzheimers disease.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
}
]
},
{
"type": "rule",
"canonical_name": "Vitamins",
"aliases": ["Essential vitamins"],
"claims": [
{
"text": "Vitamins are defined as organic compounds required for essential bodily functions including energy production immune support and skin health.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
},
{
"text": "There are thirteen main vitamins including A C D E and the B complex each serving distinct biological roles.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
},
{
"text": "Most vitamins must be obtained through diet or supplementation because the body cannot produce sufficient quantities.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
}
]
},
{
"type": "rule",
"canonical_name": "Bioavailability",
"aliases": [],
"claims": [
{
"text": "Bioavailability refers to how much of a substance enters the bloodstream and becomes available to body tissues after ingestion.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
},
{
"text": "Poor bioavailability can result in nutrients being excreted without providing benefit to the body.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
}
]
},
{
"type": "rule",
"canonical_name": "Aluminum Bioavailability",
"aliases": [],
"claims": [
{
"text": "Aluminum bioavailability describes the extent to which ingested aluminum is absorbed into the bloodstream and tissues.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
},
{
"text": "Most aluminum is normally excreted through urine or feces but certain chemical forms may increase absorption.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
}
]
},
{
"type": "rule",
"canonical_name": "Aluminum Ascorbate",
"aliases": [],
"claims": [
{
"text": "When aluminum combines with vitamin C it can form aluminum ascorbate which may influence aluminum retention in the body.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
},
{
"text": "Aluminum ascorbate is described as potentially increasing aluminum absorption under certain conditions.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
}
]
},
{
"type": "rule",
"canonical_name": "Chelation",
"aliases": ["Metal binding"],
"claims": [
{
"text": "Chelation is described as a process where compounds such as vitamin C bind metals and help remove them from the body.",
"source": "health_book_draft:chunk_4"
}
]
},
